<TITLE> Huda remanded for three days in extortion case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 24 (bdnews24.com)  Former BNP minister Nazmul Huda was remanded in custody Tuesday for three days for questioning in an extortion case. Magistrate Mir Ali Reza of Dhaka Chief Metropolitan Magistrate's Court after hearing placed Huda on remand at 12:50pm with him in the dock. Huda's lawyer advocate Sanaullah asked for time for the hearing, but the magistrate rejected the appeal. Sanaullah claimed that his client was unwell and that his remand hearing should take place once he got over. Huda, a barrister, however, said: "I'm quite okay." On July 5, Matiur Rahman filed a case Dhanmondi Police Station charging Huda with extorting Tk 1 crore. The case details said Huda demanded Tk 5 crore from Matiur but he paid the accused Tk 1 crore. On July 8, investigation officer sub-inspector Amirul Islam of Dhanmondi Police Station appealed to the court for remanding former communication minister on seven days. Huda is scheduled to appear before Dhaka District Magistrate's Court in another case filed with Dohar Police Station. bdnews24.com
